Week 4 Exercise

Revisiting the GSE100687 dataset

For these exercises, we will re-visit the dataset from last weeks exercise; the published dataset with GEO accession number GSE100687. You will need to switch to the RStudio project that you created for this dataset.

Exercise: Create a new R markdown file and add the following code chunk to read the files from the GSE100687 dataset.

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(tximport)
library(DESeq2)

sampleInfo <- read_tsv("meta_data/sampleInfo.txt")
tx2gene <- read_csv("tx2gene.csv",col_names = FALSE)

dirs <- list.files("salmon_output/")
quant_files <- list.files("salmon_output/",pattern="quant.sf",recursive = TRUE,full.names = TRUE)
names(quant_files) <- dirs
txi <- tximport(quant_files,
                type="salmon",
                tx2gene = tx2gene,
                ignoreTxVersion = TRUE)

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi, colData = sampleInfo,
                                design = ~Treated)

dds$CellLine <- as.factor(dds$CellLine)

In order to make use of the meta data we have recorded for these samples, we need to join the table to the sampleInfo data frame we created earlier. The sample identifiers (SRR) appear as rownames, and not columns in the data frame itself. The rownames_to_column function can be used to create such a column. You can now join the sampleInfo and counts into a single data frame for plotting.

plotCounts(dds, "ENSG00000000003", intgroup = "CellLine",
           returnData = TRUE) %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("SRR")

Visualise the counts using ggplot2 and colour the counts according to whether the sample has been treated or not. See below for an example, but feel free to customise the plot.

The left_join function can be used to join the counts with the sample information. It is recommended to use geom_jitter rather than geom_point to distinguish the points more easily.

We saw in the practical that a PCA plot can help us decide what the main sources of variation in our dataset are - hopefully they should be the biological contrast that we are trying to compare. Before running a PCA, it is advisable to use a variance-stablising transformation.

vsd <- vst(dds)
using 'avgTxLength' from assays(dds), correcting for library size

Exercise: Produce separate PCA plots using both CellLine and Treated as the intgroup argument. What do you notice? Do you think that the dataset will be effective at comparing Treated to Untreated samples?

Exercise: Proceed to use the DESeq function to identify genes that are differentially-expressed between treated and un-treated samples. Are you surprised by how many / how few genes have an adjusted p-value < 0.05?
